Nvidia Corporation, founded in 1993 by Jensen Huang, Chris Malachowsky, and Curtis Priem, is a pioneering American technology company known for its graphics processing units (GPUs). Initially focused on the gaming industry, Nvidia revolutionized graphics technology with the launch of the GeForce 256 in 1999, marketed as the world’s first GPU.

Throughout the 2000s, Nvidia became a dominant force in PC gaming, consistently releasing high-performance GPUs. In 2006, the company introduced CUDA, a parallel computing platform that expanded GPU applications beyond graphics, enabling breakthroughs in scientific research, artificial intelligence (AI), and data analytics.

Nvidia’s role in AI surged in the 2010s as its GPUs became the hardware of choice for deep learning and machine learning applications. High-profile partnerships and the popularity of Nvidia’s Tesla and later A100 GPUs helped establish it as a key player in AI infrastructure.

In addition to hardware, Nvidia expanded into software and systems, notably with the development of the Nvidia Drive platform for autonomous vehicles and the Nvidia Omniverse for 3D collaboration and simulation. In 2020, it announced plans to acquire ARM Holdings, a move that faced regulatory scrutiny and was ultimately abandoned in 2022.

As of the 2020s, Nvidia continues to push innovation in gaming, AI, data centers, and automotive technologies. With its RTX GPU series and leadership in AI acceleration, Nvidia remains at the forefront of the tech industry, shaping the future of visual computing and intelligent machines.

claude
